What you need to know:  This new addition to Vipingo Ridge follows the commissioning of the property as a wildlife sanctuary in 2020, offering refuge to animals facing challenges due to drought or human/animal conflictThe 2,500-acre protected estate has become a new home to waterbuck, zebra, impala, eland, Grant's gazelle, bushbuck and oryx - all part of a "space for wildlife" conservation project under the auspices of the Kenya Wildlife Service